1
00:00:10,605 --> 00:00:12,905
READY OR NOT: TEXAS

2
00:00:14,238 --> 00:00:15,438
I don't believe it.

3
00:00:20,138 --> 00:00:21,938
Are you heading to the pool?

4
00:00:22,005 --> 00:00:25,371
I'm sorry, but what are you wearing?

5
00:00:26,071 --> 00:00:27,671
It's cold.

6
00:00:27,738 --> 00:00:29,505
What are you wearing under it?

7
00:00:29,571 --> 00:00:30,838
It says "Texas."

8
00:00:30,905 --> 00:00:32,405
You've wrapped up warmly.

9
00:00:32,471 --> 00:00:33,838
DURING BREAK TIME 30 MINUTES AGO…

10
00:00:33,905 --> 00:00:35,738
What team is this store for?

11
00:00:35,805 --> 00:00:37,505
This is a basketball court.

12
00:00:37,571 --> 00:00:38,805
So, it's a basketball team?

13
00:00:38,871 --> 00:00:41,638
Well, they have a mix of everything.

14
00:00:41,705 --> 00:00:45,471
<i>I want to buy something for everyone,</i>
<i>one gift per person.</i>

15
00:00:45,538 --> 00:00:47,871
GENEROUS SPENDING AT THE TEAM SHOP

16
00:00:47,938 --> 00:00:49,238
<i>I'll buy you two things if you like.</i>

17
00:00:49,305 --> 00:00:51,605
<i>- Two?</i>
<i>- Just get everything you want.</i>

18
00:00:51,671 --> 00:00:53,705
YU-MI: TRACK TEAM HAT, FLEECE JACKET
DAE-JU: BASKETBALL HAT, ZIP-UP

19
00:00:53,771 --> 00:00:56,371
Have you shopped like this
while traveling before?

20
00:00:56,438 --> 00:00:57,938
Are you on the softball team?

21
00:00:58,005 --> 00:00:59,705
Does it say "softball" on this?

22
00:00:59,771 --> 00:01:02,071
It's written right there.
Did you buy it without looking?

23
00:01:02,138 --> 00:01:03,871
There were too many to choose from.

24
00:01:03,938 --> 00:01:06,038
I wore the Dallas Cowboys jacket on top.

25
00:01:06,105 --> 00:01:07,971
I'm cheering them on here from Austin.

26
00:01:08,038 --> 00:01:09,038
Go, Dallas Cowboys.

27
00:01:09,104 --> 00:01:10,938
- I'm also wearing NASA.
- NASA.

28
00:01:11,005 --> 00:01:12,138
DALLAS COWBOYS JACKET AND NASA FLEECE

29
00:01:12,705 --> 00:01:14,571
He only cares about himself being warm.

30
00:01:14,638 --> 00:01:16,038
- We can go now.
- Let's go.

31
00:01:16,105 --> 00:01:19,505
We look like University of Texas alumni.

32
00:01:19,571 --> 00:01:20,538
We really do.

33
00:01:20,605 --> 00:01:22,405
THE EMBLEMATIC BRIGHT BURNT ORANGE
SHINING BRIGHTLY

34
00:01:22,471 --> 00:01:25,671
PERFECTLY DRESSED
TO GO SIGHTSEEING IN AUSTIN

35
00:01:25,738 --> 00:01:27,571
Do we just get on? It's a fun ride, right?

36
00:01:27,638 --> 00:01:30,105
- This person is our driver.
- Hello.

37
00:01:44,638 --> 00:01:46,871
PEDAL PUB
PEDAL-POWERED DOWNTOWN TOUR

38
00:01:46,938 --> 00:01:48,671
YOU CAN ENJOY BOTH BEER AND MUSIC

39
00:01:48,738 --> 00:01:50,105
DUE TO COPYRIGHT ISSUES

40
00:01:50,171 --> 00:01:52,238
INSTEAD OF MUSIC,
WARM CONVERSATIONS WILL FILL THE AIR

41
00:01:52,305 --> 00:01:53,405
HOPPING ON

42
00:01:53,471 --> 00:01:55,171
We need to pedal hard.

43
00:01:55,238 --> 00:01:57,638
It's designed for Western builds.

44
00:01:57,705 --> 00:02:00,005
- Can't you reach the pedals?
- I can, but…

45
00:02:00,071 --> 00:02:02,871
ALREADY SENSING THIS WON'T BE EASY

46
00:02:07,038 --> 00:02:08,338
AUSTIN PEDAL PUB LETS YOU
BRING YOUR OWN DRINK

47
00:02:08,405 --> 00:02:09,738
AND STORES IT IN AN ICE BOX FOR YOU

48
00:02:09,805 --> 00:02:12,105
I have a good feeling about this.

49
00:02:12,171 --> 00:02:13,905
I think it will be fun.

50
00:02:13,971 --> 00:02:15,371
Are you University of Texas students?

51
00:02:15,438 --> 00:02:17,171
Are you here to meet us for a blind date?

52
00:02:17,238 --> 00:02:18,771
Hello.

53
00:02:18,838 --> 00:02:20,371
- So, you are students.
- Hello.

54
00:02:20,438 --> 00:02:21,938
We're University of Texas freshmen.

55
00:02:22,005 --> 00:02:23,671
I see. It's nice to meet you.

56
00:02:23,738 --> 00:02:25,771
- Are you on the softball team?
- No.

57
00:02:25,838 --> 00:02:27,238
I'm a dance student.

58
00:02:27,305 --> 00:02:29,105
Oh, I see. You're on the dance team.

59
00:02:29,171 --> 00:02:30,338
You look like a softball coach.

60
00:02:30,405 --> 00:02:31,338
I'm not.

61
00:02:40,338 --> 00:02:41,238
YES, SIR

62
00:02:41,305 --> 00:02:42,171
All right.

63
00:02:49,505 --> 00:02:50,405
This is interesting.

64
00:02:51,071 --> 00:02:53,638
A CHEERY AND ENERGETIC START

65
00:02:53,705 --> 00:02:55,838
<i>Let's have fun</i>

66
00:02:57,405 --> 00:02:59,738
<i>Let's pedal hard</i>

67
00:02:59,805 --> 00:03:01,738
<i>Let's have fun</i>

68
00:03:01,805 --> 00:03:03,805
TODAY'S COPYRIGHT-FREE SONG CHOICE
KOREAN FOLK CHANT

69
00:03:04,371 --> 00:03:06,871
It's such a beautiful day.

70
00:03:06,938 --> 00:03:08,371
Yes, it really is.

71
00:03:08,438 --> 00:03:11,038
IT'S THE PERFECT WEATHER FOR PEDALING

72
00:03:11,105 --> 00:03:12,438
We're going to get a little sideways.

73
00:03:15,038 --> 00:03:18,538
Sorry, but if you're sick, go home.

74
00:03:18,605 --> 00:03:19,805
Okay?

75
00:03:19,871 --> 00:03:21,905
You don't look well.

76
00:03:26,338 --> 00:03:28,605
YOU CAN'T HELP BUT BOUNCE

77
00:03:28,671 --> 00:03:29,571
This is…

78
00:03:30,271 --> 00:03:31,905
This is going to be harder than I thought.

79
00:03:31,971 --> 00:03:33,805
- When do we get to drink the beer?
- The beer?

80
00:03:34,438 --> 00:03:37,538
JUST THEN, A MOMENTARY STOP AT A RED LIGHT

81
00:03:38,838 --> 00:03:39,871
THE MOST EXCITED HE'S BEEN ON THIS TRIP

82
00:03:39,938 --> 00:03:40,938
Why is he acting like that?

83
00:03:49,005 --> 00:03:50,438
SETTING OFF AGAIN
EVEN BEFORE WE GOT THE BEER OPEN

84
00:03:51,771 --> 00:03:54,238
It feels so great when we're not pedaling.

85
00:03:57,505 --> 00:04:00,571
PEDALING AGAIN
BEFORE HE CAN FINISH SPEAKING

86
00:04:00,638 --> 00:04:03,571
We're moving so slowly,
no matter how fast we pedal.

87
00:04:04,071 --> 00:04:06,971
We could walk faster than this.

88
00:04:07,038 --> 00:04:08,205
You're right.

89
00:04:16,305 --> 00:04:19,071
PANTING

90
00:04:19,138 --> 00:04:20,905
This is as fast as it goes.

91
00:04:22,605 --> 00:04:25,338
Other people on this tour
seemed to enjoy it.

92
00:04:25,404 --> 00:04:28,405
I'm sorry,
but why aren't you out of breath?

93
00:04:28,471 --> 00:04:30,605
It's because I exercise a lot.

94
00:04:30,671 --> 00:04:32,038
QUESTIONABLE PEDALING PARTICIPATION

95
00:04:32,105 --> 00:04:34,138
I exercise regularly.

96
00:04:41,738 --> 00:04:44,171
THEY WERE TOO BUSY PEDALING
TO TAKE A SINGLE SIP

97
00:04:44,238 --> 00:04:47,371
Hello, you must be seniors
at the University of Texas.

98
00:04:47,438 --> 00:04:48,971
- No, I'm not.
- You're not?

99
00:04:49,038 --> 00:04:50,205
I'm a NASA researcher.

100
00:04:50,271 --> 00:04:51,671
PROUDLY DISPLAYING THE LOGO

101
00:04:51,738 --> 00:04:53,538
You're a man of many talents.

102
00:04:53,605 --> 00:04:55,705
- I'm going to the moon in two days.
- Are you?

103
00:05:02,605 --> 00:05:03,705
WE MUST CONQUER THE HILL BEFORE THE MOON

104
00:05:03,771 --> 00:05:05,371
This isn't easy.

105
00:05:05,438 --> 00:05:07,271
Who thought of this?

106
00:05:07,938 --> 00:05:09,505
I'm too tired to take in the view.

107
00:05:09,571 --> 00:05:10,671
TEMPORARILY LOST
THE ESSENCE OF THE PEDAL PUB

108
00:05:10,738 --> 00:05:11,905
I'm exhausted.

109
00:05:11,971 --> 00:05:14,138
BREATHTAKING CITY VIEWS YOU CAN'T MISS

110
00:05:14,205 --> 00:05:16,638
I'm so thirsty. I'm downing this beer.

111
00:05:33,071 --> 00:05:35,371
Our interpreter isn't doing his job.

112
00:05:35,438 --> 00:05:36,505
Why aren't you doing your job?

113
00:05:36,571 --> 00:05:38,571
That person is doing his job.

114
00:05:38,638 --> 00:05:42,138
He said this place manages its own power.

115
00:05:42,205 --> 00:05:43,438
SOMEWHAT SHORTENED EXPLANATION

116
00:05:43,505 --> 00:05:45,771
They do what with the power?

117
00:05:45,838 --> 00:05:48,605
They handle their own power.

118
00:05:48,671 --> 00:05:50,071
AS SEO-JIN EXPLAINED VERY SIMPLY

119
00:05:50,138 --> 00:05:52,038
AUSTIN GETS ITS POWER
FROM A CITY-OWNED COMPANY

120
00:06:01,838 --> 00:06:04,638
Is that a statue of a famous singer?

121
00:06:05,471 --> 00:06:08,238
It's a country singer, Willie Nelson.

122
00:06:08,305 --> 00:06:09,338
WILLIE NELSON (BORN IN 1933)

123
00:06:09,405 --> 00:06:11,771
MADE AUSTIN'S MUSIC GLOBALLY FAMOUS
HE'S AN ICON OF FREEDOM AND REBELLION

124
00:06:11,838 --> 00:06:13,238
MOST FAMOUS SONG: "ON THE ROAD AGAIN"

125
00:06:13,305 --> 00:06:16,238
He smoked weed like crazy.

126
00:06:16,305 --> 00:06:17,838
WILLIE NELSON FOUGHT TO LEGALIZE WEED

127
00:06:17,905 --> 00:06:20,305
Our driver mentioned that earlier.

128
00:06:20,371 --> 00:06:23,138
It smells of weed here
because of Willie Nelson.

129
00:06:23,205 --> 00:06:24,105
WILLIE NELSON

130
00:06:24,171 --> 00:06:26,671
THE PRIDE OF AUSTIN DISPLAYED
ON THE STREETS

131
00:06:27,838 --> 00:06:29,405
It's Congress Avenue.

132
00:06:29,471 --> 00:06:31,038
NEXT LOCATION: AUSTIN'S MOST ICONIC STREET

133
00:06:35,338 --> 00:06:36,471
It's right there.

134
00:06:57,171 --> 00:06:58,338
FIRST FIRE IN 1881
SECOND FIRE IN 1983

135
00:06:58,405 --> 00:06:59,338
It's impressive.

136
00:06:59,405 --> 00:07:00,305
TEMPORARY STATE CAPITOL FIRE IN 1899

137
00:07:00,371 --> 00:07:02,405
I want to be the Governor of Texas.

138
00:07:02,471 --> 00:07:03,405
What?

139
00:07:03,471 --> 00:07:05,905
MOVING PAST THE IMPRESSIVE OFFICES

140
00:07:05,971 --> 00:07:07,938
INTO THE MODERN INDUSTRIAL DISTRICT

141
00:07:08,005 --> 00:07:09,438
The sky is so clear.

142
00:07:09,505 --> 00:07:10,838
It's a beautiful city.

143
00:07:25,805 --> 00:07:27,405
AUSTIN EXPECTED TO GAIN
1 MILLION RESIDENTS IN 20 YEARS

144
00:07:27,471 --> 00:07:29,338
Is Austin a very rich city?

145
00:07:29,405 --> 00:07:30,838
Of course.

146
00:07:30,905 --> 00:07:32,538
It's home to Tesla.

147
00:07:32,605 --> 00:07:33,671
That's true.

148
00:07:33,738 --> 00:07:35,971
We might be funding Austin

149
00:07:36,038 --> 00:07:38,405
with our stock investments.

150
00:07:38,471 --> 00:07:40,438
Let's go, Tesla.

151
00:07:40,505 --> 00:07:42,671
Go, Tesla.

152
00:07:42,738 --> 00:07:46,471
SEO-JIN ROOTS FOR TESLA
AS AN INDIVIDUAL INVESTOR

153
00:07:46,538 --> 00:07:49,738
They have football matches on Sundays.

154
00:07:49,805 --> 00:07:50,938
The entire city goes wild.

155
00:07:51,905 --> 00:07:54,138
I've been all over this city.

156
00:07:54,205 --> 00:07:55,605
It feels like Fort Worth Stockyards.

157
00:07:55,671 --> 00:07:57,805
WEST SIXTH STREET
IT HAS MANY SPORTS AND ROOFTOP BARS

158
00:07:58,571 --> 00:08:01,471
Fans of each team occupy different areas.

159
00:08:01,538 --> 00:08:03,238
- The zones are divided.
- Oh, I see.

160
00:08:03,305 --> 00:08:04,805
- They have their own go-to spot.
- Yes.

161
00:08:04,871 --> 00:08:06,305
So, one team will go to that pub…

162
00:08:06,371 --> 00:08:08,538
The San Francisco 49ers will go there,

163
00:08:08,605 --> 00:08:11,438
and the Dallas Cowboys fans will go here.

164
00:08:11,505 --> 00:08:13,371
A PUB CULTURE FUELED
BY THE CITY'S LOVE OF SPORTS

165
00:08:13,438 --> 00:08:15,471
I feel like a student
of the University of Texas.

166
00:08:16,071 --> 00:08:19,505
People have reacted well to this outfit.

167
00:08:19,571 --> 00:08:23,738
When you dress like this
and run into someone,

168
00:08:23,805 --> 00:08:25,105
this is what they do.

169
00:08:25,171 --> 00:08:26,871
- What is that?
- It's the Longhorn sign.

170
00:08:26,938 --> 00:08:29,005
- Oh, is that what it is?
- Yes.

171
00:08:29,638 --> 00:08:31,571
I'm going to call the police.

172
00:08:31,638 --> 00:08:33,605
- So that's the Longhorn sign.
- Is it really?

173
00:08:33,671 --> 00:08:35,571
- Call…
- I just learned something new.

174
00:08:36,238 --> 00:08:39,005
Austin is a great place to live, Seo-jin.

175
00:08:40,938 --> 00:08:42,838
The university and all the big companies

176
00:08:42,905 --> 00:08:44,838
must have a huge impact
on the real estate.

177
00:08:44,905 --> 00:08:46,471
There are many big companies

178
00:08:46,538 --> 00:08:48,271
- other than Tesla.
- Exactly.

179
00:08:48,338 --> 00:08:52,238
Dallas had a conservative feel to it.

180
00:08:52,305 --> 00:08:54,971
Houston felt like an old rural village.

181
00:08:55,038 --> 00:08:56,738
- This place feels very youthful.
- It is.

182
00:08:57,571 --> 00:08:59,971
It's bustling with people.

183
00:09:00,038 --> 00:09:02,205
- And most of the residents are young.
- It is.

184
00:09:02,271 --> 00:09:05,371
Dallas is a city of cowboys.

185
00:09:05,438 --> 00:09:07,038
But this is a city of young people.

186
00:09:07,105 --> 00:09:08,638
A VIBRANT, GROWING CITY
FILLED WITH YOUTHFUL ENERGY

187
00:09:08,705 --> 00:09:10,005
There's another tour group.

188
00:09:10,071 --> 00:09:11,571
Can you see them enjoying the music?

189
00:09:11,638 --> 00:09:13,805
- We should have music, too.
- I like the music.

190
00:09:13,871 --> 00:09:14,805
ENCOUNTERED ANOTHER PEDAL PUB

191
00:09:14,871 --> 00:09:16,671
Hello.

192
00:09:16,738 --> 00:09:20,371
SAME PEDAL PUB, DIFFERENT VIBES

193
00:09:20,438 --> 00:09:22,605
- They beat us.
- We've lost.

194
00:09:22,671 --> 00:09:24,471
- They win.
- I wish we had music.

195
00:09:24,538 --> 00:09:26,571
PEDAL PUBS USUALLY PLAY MUSIC

196
00:09:26,638 --> 00:09:27,638
Gosh, look at them.

197
00:09:27,705 --> 00:09:28,938
DROWNING THEIR SORROW WITH BEER

198
00:09:29,005 --> 00:09:29,838
I'm jealous.

199
00:09:29,905 --> 00:09:31,438
We don't know how to have fun.

200
00:09:31,505 --> 00:09:32,738
THE YOUNG COMPANIONS BOUNCE AWAY

201
00:09:32,805 --> 00:09:34,505
It's probably the driver's first time
without music.

202
00:09:39,838 --> 00:09:42,638
YOU ARE JUST AS IMPRESSIVE

203
00:09:42,705 --> 00:09:45,938
KOREAN CELEBRITIES IN AUSTIN

204
00:09:46,005 --> 00:09:48,571
We're not sightseeing in Austin.

205
00:09:49,205 --> 00:09:52,071
We're the ones being seen.

206
00:09:52,138 --> 00:09:56,138
AUSTIN'S NEW ATTRACTION
THE BURNT ORANGE CORPS

207
00:09:56,205 --> 00:10:00,038
There are a lot of shops
that I want to visit.

208
00:10:00,105 --> 00:10:01,471
There are so many.

209
00:10:01,538 --> 00:10:02,971
MAKING A QUICK STOP
ON A STREET OF CHARMING SHOPS

210
00:10:03,038 --> 00:10:04,538
There are so many cute cafés.

211
00:10:15,605 --> 00:10:17,405
This crosswalk is so cute.

212
00:10:17,471 --> 00:10:18,638
It's an LGBT crosswalk?

213
00:10:18,705 --> 00:10:20,338
A COLORFUL LGBT-FRIENDLY STREET

214
00:10:20,405 --> 00:10:21,938
The weather is so nice.

215
00:10:28,671 --> 00:10:30,138
I sat next to a guy

216
00:10:30,205 --> 00:10:31,605
who won't do any interpreting or pedaling.

217
00:10:31,671 --> 00:10:32,871
So, my thighs are burning.

218
00:10:33,771 --> 00:10:35,505
Stand next to Seo-jin.

219
00:10:35,571 --> 00:10:37,205
- What?
- Strike a pose.

220
00:10:37,271 --> 00:10:38,271
Strike a pose?

221
00:10:39,171 --> 00:10:42,105
UNIVERSITY OF TEXAS PROFESSORS
ON A DAY TRIP

222
00:10:42,171 --> 00:10:43,138
IGNORING HIM

223
00:10:43,205 --> 00:10:44,671
University of Texas professor.

224
00:10:44,738 --> 00:10:48,971
WE'RE CLOSER THAN WE LOOK

225
00:10:49,038 --> 00:10:50,238
THE BEER IS SERVED

226
00:10:50,305 --> 00:10:52,171
- Dae-ju, sit here.
- Okay.

227
00:10:54,905 --> 00:10:56,971
That's a self-driving taxi.

228
00:10:57,038 --> 00:10:59,071
- I want to ride one.
- It's Waymo.

229
00:10:59,138 --> 00:11:01,338
It's driverless. There's no driver.

230
00:11:01,405 --> 00:11:04,005
There's a passenger in that one.

231
00:11:04,071 --> 00:11:06,538
Sir, I want to live in Austin.

232
00:11:08,705 --> 00:11:11,038
I want to be buried here.

233
00:11:11,105 --> 00:11:13,738
Austin is a perfect fit for me.

234
00:11:13,805 --> 00:11:15,671
It's so sunny,

235
00:11:15,738 --> 00:11:18,138
and it has a youthful vibe.

236
00:11:18,205 --> 00:11:19,705
YUNG-SUK'S FAVORITE CITY HAS CHANGED AGAIN

237
00:11:19,771 --> 00:11:21,971
But seriously, the vibe here…

238
00:11:22,038 --> 00:11:24,371
Why did you insist on going to the ranch?

239
00:11:24,438 --> 00:11:25,505
SHEEPISH

240
00:11:25,571 --> 00:11:28,071
Why did you go to the ranch
if you want to live in Austin?

241
00:11:28,138 --> 00:11:29,771
I mean, seriously…

242
00:11:29,838 --> 00:11:32,605
Shouldn't you stick to one favorite
for at least a day?

243
00:11:32,671 --> 00:11:35,205
- It changes every minute.
- Hallsville is great too.

244
00:11:35,271 --> 00:11:36,938
I really love the vibe here.

245
00:11:37,005 --> 00:11:38,138
Me too.

246
00:11:38,205 --> 00:11:40,805
We haven't really seen anything yet.

247
00:11:40,871 --> 00:11:44,805
There's an area that has
an even more youthful vibe.

248
00:11:44,871 --> 00:11:46,338
There are many malls.

249
00:11:46,405 --> 00:11:48,905
I heard Austin has
its own version of Seongsu-dong.

250
00:11:48,971 --> 00:11:49,871
That's the place.

251
00:11:49,938 --> 00:11:51,538
SEO-JIN IS REFERRING
TO SOUTH CONGRESS AVENUE

252
00:11:51,605 --> 00:11:52,605
We need to cross the bridge.

253
00:11:52,671 --> 00:11:56,538
Let's get this pedal tour over with,
and go chat in a café.

254
00:11:57,371 --> 00:11:58,571
Why do you want it to be over?

255
00:11:58,638 --> 00:11:59,871
- My legs hurt too much.
- Really?

256
00:11:59,938 --> 00:12:01,271
TOURING AUSTIN WAS WORTH THE SORE LEGS

257
00:12:01,338 --> 00:12:02,338
I told you not to pedal.

258
00:12:05,338 --> 00:12:07,805
It's called Toasty Badger.

259
00:12:07,871 --> 00:12:09,305
The food looks great.

260
00:12:09,371 --> 00:12:11,071
THE LAST DAY OF THE TRIP
BEGINS WITH BRUNCH

261
00:12:11,138 --> 00:12:13,038
The weather is stunning yet again.

262
00:12:13,105 --> 00:12:16,038
I have the hat that Dae-ju bought me.

263
00:12:19,838 --> 00:12:20,905
Don't you think

264
00:12:20,971 --> 00:12:24,438
it's weird to wear an outdoor hat
with a Ralph Lauren outfit?

265
00:12:24,505 --> 00:12:26,171
A STRANGE OLD MONEY LOOK

266
00:12:26,238 --> 00:12:28,171
It doesn't look right.

267
00:12:28,238 --> 00:12:30,505
It's the perfect day
for brunch and an outing.

268
00:12:30,571 --> 00:12:31,638
A NICE DRIVE IN PERFECT WEATHER

269
00:12:31,705 --> 00:12:33,438
We got lucky with the weather.

270
00:12:35,038 --> 00:12:37,605
DRIVING RIGHT NEXT TO COLORADO RIVER

271
00:12:37,671 --> 00:12:38,805
What a beautiful river.

272
00:12:38,871 --> 00:12:40,671
It's the Colorado River.

273
00:12:40,738 --> 00:12:42,271
This is the Batman bridge.

274
00:12:42,338 --> 00:12:44,505
- It's home to a bat colony.
- There are bats?

275
00:12:44,571 --> 00:12:46,238
It's so pretty.

276
00:12:46,305 --> 00:12:48,171
- This city is so pretty.
- It is.

277
00:12:48,238 --> 00:12:49,238
CONGRESS AVENUE BRIDGE
HOME TO MANY BATS

278
00:12:49,305 --> 00:12:52,005
This is the place you said was popular.

279
00:12:52,071 --> 00:12:53,505
The shopping district begins here.

280
00:12:53,571 --> 00:12:55,371
There's New Balance and Birkenstock.

281
00:12:55,938 --> 00:12:58,605
SOUTH OF THE COLORADO RIVER

282
00:12:58,671 --> 00:13:04,905
A DISTRICT FILLED WITH DISTINCTIVE STORES

283
00:13:05,705 --> 00:13:10,805
AUSTIN'S TRENDY SHOPPING DISTRICT
SOUTH CONGRESS AVENUE

284
00:13:10,871 --> 00:13:13,838
- Seo-jin, this place is great.
- I love the vibe.

285
00:13:13,905 --> 00:13:15,971
I like that it's not
some stuffy shopping mall,

286
00:13:16,038 --> 00:13:18,538
and you can stroll around outdoors
while you browse.

287
00:13:18,605 --> 00:13:19,705
Right?

288
00:13:19,771 --> 00:13:20,971
I like a good stroll.

289
00:13:21,038 --> 00:13:23,071
This area's perfect for a stroll.

290
00:13:23,138 --> 00:13:25,371
- I really love it here.
- It's very pretty.

291
00:13:25,438 --> 00:13:26,771
Only in America, right?

292
00:13:27,571 --> 00:13:28,638
Don't you think so?

293
00:13:28,705 --> 00:13:29,638
It's well-designed.

294
00:13:29,705 --> 00:13:31,138
This place has everything.

295
00:13:31,205 --> 00:13:33,805
You can find anything you want in America.

296
00:13:33,871 --> 00:13:36,038
- This place is also pretty.
- It's the Toasty Badger.

297
00:13:39,438 --> 00:13:42,471
AT THE HEART OF SOUTH CONGRESS AVENUE

298
00:13:42,538 --> 00:13:46,071
A CHARMING, CASUAL RESTAURANT

299
00:13:46,138 --> 00:13:48,938
A COZY INTERIOR DESIGN

300
00:13:49,005 --> 00:13:53,071
A BOUNTIFUL MENU

301
00:13:53,138 --> 00:13:56,671
AN AESTHETIC AUSTIN BRUNCH CAFÉ

302
00:13:56,738 --> 00:13:59,771
WELCOME TO AUSTIN

303
00:13:59,838 --> 00:14:02,838
ENTERING CHEERFULLY

304
00:14:02,905 --> 00:14:04,471
This place has a great vibe.

305
00:14:04,538 --> 00:14:06,038
SEO-JIN'S FAVORITE DINER-STYLE VIBE

306
00:14:08,238 --> 00:14:10,205
I want to try something new.

307
00:14:10,771 --> 00:14:14,171
I have a good feeling
about this avocado toast.

308
00:14:14,238 --> 00:14:17,671
I think you'll be disappointed.

309
00:14:17,738 --> 00:14:18,905
Why?

310
00:14:18,971 --> 00:14:22,071
It's just toast with an avocado.

311
00:14:22,138 --> 00:14:23,571
What are you going to eat?

312
00:14:25,105 --> 00:14:28,338
I might go for the breakfast sandwich.

313
00:14:28,405 --> 00:14:31,971
It contains pork, sausage, patty,
sunny egg, American cheese…

314
00:14:32,038 --> 00:14:34,738
YUNG-SUK IS STRUGGLING TO DECIDE

315
00:14:34,805 --> 00:14:36,905
I'm going to have the Fried Chicken Sando.

316
00:14:37,938 --> 00:14:39,271
What do you think?

317
00:14:39,338 --> 00:14:41,138
Have it. What's there to think about?

318
00:14:41,205 --> 00:14:42,905
It's a lunch dish.

319
00:14:42,971 --> 00:14:44,505
Then, I'll go for the avocado toast.

320
00:14:44,571 --> 00:14:45,638
Gosh, what should I have?

321
00:14:45,705 --> 00:14:46,605
I'll have the avocado.

322
00:14:46,671 --> 00:14:47,805
Just order both.

323
00:14:47,871 --> 00:14:49,271
I can't.

324
00:14:49,338 --> 00:14:50,805
I don't want to waste food.

325
00:14:51,371 --> 00:14:54,038
I'll order one,
and you can order the other.

326
00:14:54,105 --> 00:14:55,271
Thank you, Ye-seul.

327
00:15:14,938 --> 00:15:16,305
Do you want to add an egg?

328
00:15:19,705 --> 00:15:20,671
ORDERING TO YUNG-SUK'S TASTE

329
00:15:25,705 --> 00:15:26,571
ORDER COMPLETED WITH A COMPLIMENT

330
00:15:32,038 --> 00:15:33,605
Don't sing.

331
00:15:35,005 --> 00:15:37,138
I heard enough songs this morning.

332
00:15:38,205 --> 00:15:40,071
- You mean in your room?
- Yes, before check-out.

333
00:15:40,671 --> 00:15:42,805
I listened to music for two hours.

334
00:15:42,871 --> 00:15:44,605
WITHDRAWAL EFFECTS OF A WEEK WITHOUT MUSIC

335
00:15:44,671 --> 00:15:45,638
You got your music fix.

336
00:15:45,705 --> 00:15:48,805
"Lee Seo-jin's Music Journey"
would be a fun series.

337
00:15:48,871 --> 00:15:50,938
How much would that cost?

338
00:15:51,005 --> 00:15:54,371
There's so much you could talk about.

339
00:15:55,638 --> 00:15:57,205
They're wearing a half-zip.

340
00:15:58,205 --> 00:15:59,938
Well, it's a half-button.

341
00:16:00,005 --> 00:16:01,338
There's a half-zip here.

342
00:16:01,405 --> 00:16:02,271
You're right.

343
00:16:02,338 --> 00:16:04,005
America is the country of half-zips.

344
00:16:04,071 --> 00:16:06,405
- It's a country of half-zip shirts.
- It's what?

345
00:16:06,971 --> 00:16:08,305
Try on a half-zip.

346
00:16:08,371 --> 00:16:12,205
"America is a country of half-zips"
is such a stupid thing to say.

347
00:16:12,271 --> 00:16:13,971
But you see them everywhere.

348
00:16:14,038 --> 00:16:15,705
So many people wear half-zip pullovers.

349
00:16:15,771 --> 00:16:16,605
If you ask me,

350
00:16:16,671 --> 00:16:18,771
Americans love half-zips
and one more thing.

351
00:16:18,838 --> 00:16:19,905
- What?
- Check patterns.

352
00:16:19,971 --> 00:16:21,305
- Check patterns?
- Yes.

353
00:16:21,371 --> 00:16:23,605
Look over there.
One person's wearing a half-zip.

354
00:16:23,671 --> 00:16:24,538
Half-zip…

355
00:16:24,605 --> 00:16:26,371
It's half-button, but still…

356
00:16:26,438 --> 00:16:28,071
That person is wearing a checked shirt.

357
00:16:28,138 --> 00:16:29,905
HALF-BUTTON

358
00:16:30,471 --> 00:16:32,238
CHECK PATTERN

359
00:16:32,305 --> 00:16:34,605
Americans love half-zips
and check patterns.

360
00:16:34,671 --> 00:16:37,271
There's one thing I've noticed.

361
00:16:37,338 --> 00:16:40,438
People dress very differently
depending on the time of day.

362
00:16:40,505 --> 00:16:43,671
If you go to a nice restaurant at night,
everyone is dressed up.

363
00:16:43,738 --> 00:16:45,738
If you go to a brunch café in the day,

364
00:16:45,805 --> 00:16:47,038
no one is dressed up at all.

365
00:16:47,105 --> 00:16:48,971
You only see hoodies and zip-up pullovers.

366
00:16:49,038 --> 00:16:51,471
We didn't have hoodies in Korea
when I was young.

367
00:16:51,538 --> 00:16:52,505
CAPTAIN AMERICA SPEAKS AGAIN

368
00:16:52,571 --> 00:16:54,905
- Really?
- You only saw them in Itaewon.

369
00:16:54,971 --> 00:16:56,305
Hoodies weren't a thing yet.

370
00:16:56,371 --> 00:16:58,838
But Americans wore them even back then.

371
00:16:58,905 --> 00:17:00,605
They're an American invention.

372
00:17:00,671 --> 00:17:02,638
HOODIE: ORIGINALLY WINTER WEAR IN AMERICA
NOW AN ICON OF CASUAL FASHION

373
00:17:02,705 --> 00:17:04,405
<i>American capitalism.</i>

374
00:17:06,971 --> 00:17:09,071
Everyone here looks so strong and tough.

375
00:17:09,138 --> 00:17:11,271
But they're all so smiley and friendly.

376
00:17:11,338 --> 00:17:12,505
They're built so tough and sturdy,

377
00:17:12,571 --> 00:17:15,138
but they greet you so gently.

378
00:17:15,205 --> 00:17:18,938
I think it's because the state of Texas

379
00:17:19,005 --> 00:17:20,638
is very sports-driven.

380
00:17:20,705 --> 00:17:22,071
- Basically…
- You're not kidding.

381
00:17:22,138 --> 00:17:24,538
…everyone starts working out
from a young age.

382
00:17:24,604 --> 00:17:26,938
There are so many schools here,

383
00:17:27,005 --> 00:17:29,171
but the field narrows as you age.

384
00:17:29,238 --> 00:17:31,338
Only a select few
can join the professional leagues.

385
00:17:31,405 --> 00:17:34,605
So everyone grows up being really active.

386
00:17:34,671 --> 00:17:39,205
Imagine you're born again
as a Texas high school student.

387
00:17:39,271 --> 00:17:40,705
What sport would you choose?

388
00:17:40,771 --> 00:17:42,938
- I'd play football, of course.
- Seo-jin.

389
00:17:43,005 --> 00:17:45,438
PICTURING SEO-JIN'S HIGH SCHOOL MUSICAL

390
00:17:45,505 --> 00:17:47,171
- You don't agree?
- You're not muscular, so…

391
00:17:48,771 --> 00:17:50,538
QUICK TO COMPROMISE

392
00:17:50,605 --> 00:17:53,971
I was a tennis player
during my American high school days.

393
00:17:54,038 --> 00:17:55,638
I played for my school.

394
00:17:55,705 --> 00:17:57,871
There were nine players in total.

395
00:17:57,938 --> 00:18:01,438
The top five played the singles.

396
00:18:01,505 --> 00:18:03,805
The remaining four players…

397
00:18:04,705 --> 00:18:05,805
We played doubles.

398
00:18:05,871 --> 00:18:08,138
I was a first pick for the doubles.

399
00:18:08,205 --> 00:18:09,805
- If someone got sick…
- You played singles?

400
00:18:09,871 --> 00:18:11,938
Yes, I was fifth in line to play singles.

401
00:18:12,005 --> 00:18:13,871
So, you bordered on 4th and 5th place.

402
00:18:13,938 --> 00:18:15,538
- It was more like 5th and 6th.
- I see.

403
00:18:15,605 --> 00:18:17,438
SEO-JIN ON THE EDGE OF THE RANKS

404
00:18:17,505 --> 00:18:20,671
Why have I never seen you play tennis?

405
00:18:20,738 --> 00:18:22,471
I haven't picked up a racket since then.

406
00:18:22,538 --> 00:18:25,971
But you love to exercise.
Don't you miss it?

407
00:18:26,038 --> 00:18:28,238
Strangely enough,

408
00:18:28,305 --> 00:18:31,005
once I stop playing a sport,
I never want to go back.

409
00:18:31,071 --> 00:18:33,205
It was the same with boxing.

410
00:18:33,271 --> 00:18:36,138
I got to the sparring stage
and decided I was done with it.

411
00:18:36,205 --> 00:18:37,505
I haven't touched a glove since.

412
00:18:37,571 --> 00:18:41,305
As you know,
I did rock climbing at Mount Bukhan.

413
00:18:41,371 --> 00:18:43,271
I haven't gone climbing since.

414
00:18:43,338 --> 00:18:45,938
You learn the basics of everything.

415
00:18:46,005 --> 00:18:47,738
Yes, but I stop once I learn the basics.

416
00:18:47,805 --> 00:18:49,471
SERIAL SPORTS AMATEUR

417
00:18:51,738 --> 00:18:53,338
- Thank you.
- The portions are huge.

418
00:19:01,338 --> 00:19:02,738
- Thank you.
- It's plated so nicely.

419
00:19:02,805 --> 00:19:04,671
I've never seen such
nice-looking hash browns.

420
00:19:04,738 --> 00:19:05,805
Right?

421
00:19:05,871 --> 00:19:08,071
- I haven't seen a muffin in a while.
- Same.

422
00:19:10,271 --> 00:19:12,705
YUNG-SUK'S AVOCADO TOAST

423
00:19:12,771 --> 00:19:15,138
It looks difficult to eat.

424
00:19:15,205 --> 00:19:17,305
- Not this again.
- It's going to get messy.

425
00:19:17,371 --> 00:19:18,805
You're going to use your hands again.

426
00:19:18,871 --> 00:19:21,838
You'll lick all ten fingers.

427
00:19:21,905 --> 00:19:23,771
Just use a knife and fork.

428
00:19:23,838 --> 00:19:26,471
I think I'm going to make a mess.

429
00:19:26,538 --> 00:19:29,005
I'm scared to touch it.

430
00:19:29,071 --> 00:19:31,905
I made Ye-seul order what I wanted.

431
00:19:31,971 --> 00:19:33,805
- I know.
- But even that looks hard to eat.

432
00:19:33,871 --> 00:19:36,571
I'd suggest taking the chicken out.

433
00:19:36,638 --> 00:19:37,971
Why is it so big?

434
00:19:38,038 --> 00:19:39,438
TEXAS-SIZED FRIED CHICKEN
EVEN FINGER LICKING NA IS AFRAID OF

435
00:19:39,505 --> 00:19:40,338
I'm so happy.

436
00:19:40,405 --> 00:19:41,771
Oh, Ye-seul. You shouldn't.

437
00:19:41,838 --> 00:19:42,671
GRABS EAGERLY

438
00:19:42,738 --> 00:19:44,571
I told you I didn't want it.

439
00:19:44,638 --> 00:19:47,538
I used my hands without thinking.

440
00:19:47,605 --> 00:19:49,971
It's okay because I just showered, right?

441
00:19:50,038 --> 00:19:51,538
- Do you want a bite?
- This is…

442
00:19:51,605 --> 00:19:52,771
This is just the beginning.

443
00:19:52,838 --> 00:19:55,505
YUNG-SUK SHOWERED THIS MORNING,
AND SEO-JIN HAS GIVEN UP

444
00:19:55,571 --> 00:19:57,538
This is how another day begins.

445
00:19:57,605 --> 00:19:59,905
CRUNCH

446
00:19:59,971 --> 00:20:02,805
A BIG BITE OF THE SANDWICH HE DIDN'T WANT

447
00:20:02,871 --> 00:20:04,938
I think this is the best.

448
00:20:05,005 --> 00:20:06,371
- I chose well, didn't I?
- You did.

449
00:20:07,105 --> 00:20:08,971
GULPING IT DOWN

450
00:20:09,038 --> 00:20:12,138
THE GENTLEMAN ALSO SEEMS SATISFIED

451
00:20:12,205 --> 00:20:14,305
Let's try Dae-ju's ham.

452
00:20:14,371 --> 00:20:15,571
Aren't you having the avocado?

453
00:20:16,305 --> 00:20:18,571
- I think he's scared to touch it.
- Are you?

454
00:20:18,638 --> 00:20:20,638
I'm worried I'll make a mess.

455
00:20:20,705 --> 00:20:22,605
BUFFET-STYLE FEAST

456
00:20:22,671 --> 00:20:23,971
- Okay, here I go.
- Time for the avocado.

457
00:20:24,038 --> 00:20:25,838
I'm going for it.

458
00:20:25,905 --> 00:20:27,738
I want to give half of it
to our sweet Ye-seul.

459
00:20:27,805 --> 00:20:29,805
- I'm okay.
- No, I'm giving you half.

460
00:20:29,871 --> 00:20:32,438
It's because it's too big.
He can't eat it all.

461
00:20:33,805 --> 00:20:35,938
I'm doing this for the sake of content.

462
00:20:36,771 --> 00:20:38,905
All I care about is
the filming process, Ye-seul.

463
00:20:38,971 --> 00:20:41,005
I'm not here to have fun.

464
00:20:41,071 --> 00:20:42,505
I'm doing this all for content.

465
00:20:43,138 --> 00:20:46,771
MOUTH-WATERING CLIP INSERTED

466
00:20:46,838 --> 00:20:50,605
ACCEPTS IT AGAINST HER WILL

467
00:20:50,671 --> 00:20:52,505
All right. It's my turn now.

468
00:20:54,405 --> 00:20:57,305
I'm determined not to use my hands.

469
00:20:57,371 --> 00:20:59,571
I like that plan.

470
00:21:00,771 --> 00:21:03,005
Let me try some.

471
00:21:04,905 --> 00:21:07,038
AMAZED

472
00:21:07,105 --> 00:21:08,771
It tastes so good
it makes your eyes widen.

473
00:21:08,838 --> 00:21:09,705
Who are you talking to?

474
00:21:09,771 --> 00:21:12,105
- The camera's focused on Seo-jin.
- Is it?

475
00:21:12,171 --> 00:21:13,305
You need to look into that camera.

476
00:21:13,371 --> 00:21:14,505
YUNG-SUK'S WIDE EYES WERE OUT OF FRAME

477
00:21:14,571 --> 00:21:16,171
Aren't you a TV producer?

478
00:21:18,571 --> 00:21:20,971
Why is a TV producer
looking into the wrong camera?

479
00:21:21,038 --> 00:21:22,338
When did you switch cameras?

480
00:21:25,605 --> 00:21:27,438
THE CAMERA HAS BEEN
ON SEO-JIN FROM THE START

481
00:21:27,505 --> 00:21:29,771
Here's the chicken sandwich.
I'm really looking forward to it.

482
00:21:29,838 --> 00:21:32,471
Aren't the cameras
usually set up like this?

483
00:21:32,538 --> 00:21:34,438
Shouldn't a TV producer know this?

484
00:21:34,505 --> 00:21:36,171
EMBARRASSED

485
00:21:36,238 --> 00:21:38,038
He's lost his touch
with this kind of thing.

486
00:21:38,105 --> 00:21:39,538
It makes your eyes widen.

487
00:21:39,605 --> 00:21:41,271
I thought you only cared
about the filming process?

488
00:21:41,338 --> 00:21:42,338
TIME FOR A STROLL TO DIGEST

489
00:21:42,405 --> 00:21:44,138
Ye-seul, this place is great.

490
00:21:44,205 --> 00:21:46,205
A PLACE WITH STUNNING VIEWS

491
00:21:46,271 --> 00:21:49,238
AN OASIS IN THE MIDDLE OF DOWNTOWN AUSTIN

492
00:21:50,305 --> 00:21:51,771
Look at this.

493
00:21:51,838 --> 00:21:52,838
This is insane.

494
00:21:55,538 --> 00:21:58,371
A SWIMMING HOLE
THAT IS THOUSANDS OF YEARS OLD

495
00:21:58,438 --> 00:22:01,705
It's a natural swimming pool.

496
00:22:01,771 --> 00:22:03,738
Did you bring swimwear?

497
00:22:03,805 --> 00:22:04,738
You didn't bring any?

498
00:22:05,405 --> 00:22:06,605
NODS

499
00:22:06,671 --> 00:22:08,738
NO CHOICE BUT TO JUST OBSERVE

500
00:22:08,805 --> 00:22:11,971
IT'S A BEAUTIFUL SIGHT JUST TO LOOK AT

501
00:22:12,038 --> 00:22:15,238
A NATURAL RESTING PLACE FOR THE LOCALS

502
00:22:15,305 --> 00:22:19,638
A PLACE WHERE ALL PEOPLE

503
00:22:20,205 --> 00:22:24,571
CAN FREELY ENJOY THE SPRING WEATHER

504
00:22:25,305 --> 00:22:27,671
LET'S TAKE A BREAK HERE BEFORE MOVING ON!

505
00:22:27,738 --> 00:22:29,871
Let's rest under that tree.

506
00:22:29,938 --> 00:22:31,071
It's in the shade.

507
00:22:31,805 --> 00:22:32,938
Let's head to that big tree.

508
00:22:33,005 --> 00:22:34,238
LOOKING FOR THE PERFECT RESTING SPOT

509
00:22:34,305 --> 00:22:37,105
IN THE SHADE

510
00:22:37,171 --> 00:22:39,771
Should we sit partially in the shade?

511
00:22:39,838 --> 00:22:41,638
Everyone else is sitting in the sun.

512
00:22:41,705 --> 00:22:43,138
So let's sit somewhere in the middle.

513
00:22:44,138 --> 00:22:46,138
GENTLY

514
00:22:46,205 --> 00:22:50,038
SET-UP COMPLETE
PERFECT BALANCE OF SUN AND SHADE

515
00:22:50,105 --> 00:22:52,871
SEO-JIN IS BUSY TAKING IN THE VIEW

516
00:22:52,938 --> 00:22:54,605
Seo-jin, come and sit.

517
00:22:54,671 --> 00:22:55,938
Have some water.

518
00:22:56,005 --> 00:22:59,338
HE DECIDES TO SIT AND TAKE IN THE VIEW

519
00:23:00,971 --> 00:23:03,905
SITTING COZILY TOGETHER
ON THE UNIVERSITY OF TEXAS BLANKET

520
00:23:04,471 --> 00:23:07,905
LET'S PHOTOSYNTHESIZE

521
00:23:08,571 --> 00:23:09,771
Goodness.

522
00:23:09,838 --> 00:23:12,605
America's got everything.

523
00:23:13,338 --> 00:23:15,305
No, it's not America.

524
00:23:15,371 --> 00:23:16,305
It's Austin.

525
00:23:17,038 --> 00:23:18,238
CAPTAIN AMERICA'S COMPETITION:
CAPTAIN AUSTIN

526
00:23:18,305 --> 00:23:19,338
Austin's got everything.

527
00:23:20,071 --> 00:23:22,938
I'm going to spend
the last third of my life in Austin.

528
00:23:23,505 --> 00:23:24,538
What about the middle third?

529
00:23:24,605 --> 00:23:25,538
The middle third?

530
00:23:25,605 --> 00:23:27,305
I spent it in New York.

531
00:23:27,371 --> 00:23:29,305
- It's already past?
- I spent it in New York.

532
00:23:29,371 --> 00:23:30,405
I see.

533
00:23:31,471 --> 00:23:33,005
That pool is eight feet deep.

534
00:23:33,071 --> 00:23:35,305
- It's a bit less than that.
- It's so deep.

535
00:23:35,371 --> 00:23:37,838
It was five feet deep on the other side.

536
00:23:37,905 --> 00:23:38,971
That side is five feet.

537
00:23:39,038 --> 00:23:41,638
- Five feet's enough to stand in.
- But this side is eight feet.

538
00:23:41,705 --> 00:23:42,905
Don't worry about it.

539
00:23:42,971 --> 00:23:44,238
We don't have any swimwear.

540
00:23:45,171 --> 00:23:46,538
I brought mine.

541
00:23:46,605 --> 00:23:48,038
- Did you?
- You brought swimwear?

542
00:23:48,105 --> 00:23:49,771
- I did, but…
- Really?

543
00:23:49,838 --> 00:23:51,538
Hey, Dae-ju brought swimwear.

544
00:23:51,605 --> 00:23:53,605
But I can't swim.

545
00:23:53,671 --> 00:23:54,838
You can swim in the shallow end.

546
00:23:54,905 --> 00:23:56,238
Where?

547
00:23:56,305 --> 00:23:58,771
Just jump into the water here.

548
00:24:00,005 --> 00:24:01,771
You just need to stay afloat.

549
00:24:02,471 --> 00:24:04,571
You can change up there.

550
00:24:04,638 --> 00:24:06,805
We need to cover him with this.

551
00:24:06,871 --> 00:24:09,571
But I really don't know how to swim.

552
00:24:10,138 --> 00:24:11,271
Let's get you changed.

553
00:24:11,338 --> 00:24:13,338
I guess we need to get moving.

554
00:24:13,405 --> 00:24:15,238
GETTING UP TO MAKE HIM DO IT

555
00:24:15,305 --> 00:24:16,138
Here we go.

556
00:24:16,638 --> 00:24:17,905
We'll wrap this around you.

557
00:24:17,971 --> 00:24:19,705
Do you want us in front or behind you?

558
00:24:19,771 --> 00:24:21,371
We can circle it around him.

559
00:24:21,438 --> 00:24:22,605
But…

560
00:24:22,671 --> 00:24:24,305
All right. Now come inside.

561
00:24:24,371 --> 00:24:25,505
- There you go.
- That's it.

562
00:24:25,571 --> 00:24:26,938
- This works.
- It does.

563
00:24:27,005 --> 00:24:28,838
PERFECTLY TRAPPED

564
00:24:28,905 --> 00:24:31,138
I'm telling you I can't swim.

565
00:24:31,205 --> 00:24:32,805
Yung-suk's a good swimmer.

566
00:24:32,871 --> 00:24:34,138
Get changed already.

567
00:24:34,205 --> 00:24:36,338
OUTFIT CHANGE BEGINS

568
00:24:36,405 --> 00:24:37,971
I'll make sure you're covered.

569
00:24:38,038 --> 00:24:40,371
We need to protect your privacy.

570
00:24:40,438 --> 00:24:42,038
Oh, jeez.

571
00:24:42,105 --> 00:24:43,471
It's windy, Dae-ju.

572
00:24:43,538 --> 00:24:45,071
It's really windy.

573
00:24:45,138 --> 00:24:46,305
There's a camera behind you.

574
00:24:48,171 --> 00:24:49,805
- Behind you…
- There's a camera.

575
00:24:49,871 --> 00:24:51,071
ACCIDENTALLY RISKY CAMERA PLACEMENT

576
00:24:51,138 --> 00:24:52,405
Dae-ju, you need to turn this way.

577
00:24:52,471 --> 00:24:53,738
- There's a camera behind you.
- Oh, man.

578
00:24:53,805 --> 00:24:54,671
It's okay.

579
00:24:54,738 --> 00:24:55,938
- You're out of frame.
- It's fine.

580
00:24:56,005 --> 00:24:57,871
LUCKILY, DAE-JU'S PRIVACY IS SAFE

581
00:24:58,438 --> 00:25:00,571
I don't believe this.

582
00:25:00,638 --> 00:25:01,605
Lower the blanket.

583
00:25:01,671 --> 00:25:02,538
Wait a minute.

584
00:25:02,605 --> 00:25:03,505
CHUCKLING

585
00:25:03,571 --> 00:25:04,405
CHANGE COMPLETE DESPITE OBSTACLES

586
00:25:04,471 --> 00:25:05,738
- Are you done?
- I'm done.

587
00:25:06,305 --> 00:25:07,638
- I'll just take a quick dip.
- Dae-ju.

588
00:25:07,705 --> 00:25:09,705
- Dip your feet in first.
- Okay.

589
00:25:10,305 --> 00:25:12,805
I can't go in deeper anyway.
I'll be back out in a flash.

590
00:25:12,871 --> 00:25:14,005
Get in already.

591
00:25:14,071 --> 00:25:15,838
WORRIED SEO-JIN HAS COME TO WATCH

592
00:25:15,905 --> 00:25:18,705
You're not going to save me, are you?

593
00:25:20,805 --> 00:25:22,971
If I wasn't scared, I'd dive in.

594
00:25:23,038 --> 00:25:24,705
Try it. Don't be scared.

595
00:25:24,771 --> 00:25:26,605
There's a railing here.
What's to be afraid of?

596
00:25:26,671 --> 00:25:28,805
READY TO ENTER WITH SEO-JIN'S SUPPORT

597
00:25:31,238 --> 00:25:32,538
Is it cold?

598
00:25:32,605 --> 00:25:34,038
- Is it cold?
- I'm just scared.

599
00:25:34,105 --> 00:25:35,771
A TENSE START

600
00:25:36,338 --> 00:25:39,205
TENSION-MELTING SUNLIGHT

601
00:25:41,038 --> 00:25:43,571
DAE-JU RELAXES INTO THE CALM WATER

602
00:25:43,638 --> 00:25:45,338
My feet reach the bottom.

603
00:25:45,405 --> 00:25:46,305
I told you so.

604
00:25:46,371 --> 00:25:47,238
GOT COMFORTABLE

605
00:25:47,305 --> 00:25:48,471
Now put your head under the water.

606
00:25:48,538 --> 00:25:50,471
BACKSEAT DRIVING FROM A JEALOUS OBSERVER

607
00:25:51,671 --> 00:25:53,205
That's it.

608
00:25:53,271 --> 00:25:54,105
You did it.

609
00:25:54,171 --> 00:25:55,271
SEMI-DIVE SUCCESSFUL

610
00:25:55,338 --> 00:25:56,405
SO REFRESHING

611
00:25:56,471 --> 00:25:58,871
- I'll try to get there.
- Okay.

612
00:25:59,438 --> 00:26:01,471
FLOUNDERING

613
00:26:01,538 --> 00:26:03,538
IT'S FUN JUST FLAILING AROUND

614
00:26:04,771 --> 00:26:06,805
EVEN A LIGHT DIP IS REFRESHING

615
00:26:07,605 --> 00:26:09,671
MELTING INTO THE BEAUTIFUL SCENERY

616
00:26:09,738 --> 00:26:11,438
I need to do some sunbathing.

617
00:26:11,505 --> 00:26:14,771
LYING ON THE GRASS SOAKING IN THE SUN

618
00:26:14,838 --> 00:26:16,738
It's so refreshing.
Someone else should try it.

619
00:26:16,805 --> 00:26:17,838
The water feels so nice.

620
00:26:17,905 --> 00:26:19,205
CHUCKLING

621
00:26:19,271 --> 00:26:20,638
Who else could go in?

622
00:26:20,705 --> 00:26:22,005
No one else has swimwear.

623
00:26:22,071 --> 00:26:23,238
I'll lend them mine.

624
00:26:23,305 --> 00:26:24,905
THE PICNIC IS IN FULL SWING

625
00:26:27,938 --> 00:26:30,138
AUSTIN STUDENTS STRIKE UP SMALL TALK

626
00:26:35,971 --> 00:26:38,005
SEO-JIN ANSWERING AS THE PROGRAM FRONTMAN

627
00:26:40,438 --> 00:26:41,705
A FOND SMILE

628
00:26:43,505 --> 00:26:44,471
Oh, yes?

629
00:26:44,538 --> 00:26:46,771
AFTER A SWEET CHAT WITH THE STUDENTS…

630
00:26:47,371 --> 00:26:50,071
<i>Is the Austin roller rink next?</i>

631
00:26:50,138 --> 00:26:51,805
Tell us before we get there.

632
00:26:51,871 --> 00:26:53,738
How good are you at roller skating?

633
00:26:53,805 --> 00:26:55,738
Let's all rate ourselves.

634
00:26:56,471 --> 00:26:58,638
There's also a roller rink.

635
00:26:58,705 --> 00:27:00,605
- Do you skate?
- I'm a great skater.

636
00:27:00,671 --> 00:27:02,171
- Really?
- It was trendy in my time.

637
00:27:02,238 --> 00:27:03,705
I'm really good at roller skating.

638
00:27:03,771 --> 00:27:04,838
What about you, Seo-jin?

639
00:27:04,905 --> 00:27:06,038
- What?
- Do you skate?

640
00:27:06,105 --> 00:27:07,405
- Do I roller skate?
- Yes.

641
00:27:07,471 --> 00:27:08,438
SEO-JIN SAID…

642
00:27:08,505 --> 00:27:09,438
I can skate backwards.

643
00:27:09,505 --> 00:27:10,638
- Really?
- What did he say?

644
00:27:10,705 --> 00:27:11,838
- He skates backwards.
- Really?

645
00:27:11,905 --> 00:27:12,905
SKILLFUL CONFIDENCE

646
00:27:12,971 --> 00:27:15,138
I think the roller rink is a good idea.

647
00:27:15,205 --> 00:27:18,171
Hasn't it been about 30 or 40 years
since you last skated?

648
00:27:18,238 --> 00:27:20,671
It's been 40 years.
I haven't skated since middle school.

649
00:27:21,405 --> 00:27:22,705
- Can you skate forward?
- What?

650
00:27:22,771 --> 00:27:23,771
Can you skate forward?

651
00:27:24,938 --> 00:27:26,438
I'm not sure.

652
00:27:27,338 --> 00:27:29,671
CONFIDENCE VANISHING

653
00:27:29,738 --> 00:27:31,605
Okay, can you stand on skates?

654
00:27:32,771 --> 00:27:33,971
I mean…

655
00:27:35,271 --> 00:27:37,838
It's hard enough standing in normal shoes.

656
00:27:37,905 --> 00:27:40,205
SEO-JIN FINDS IT HARD TO STAND IN GENERAL

657
00:27:40,271 --> 00:27:41,471
Darn it.

658
00:27:42,371 --> 00:27:44,271
I don't want to embarrass myself.

659
00:27:44,338 --> 00:27:46,205
WILL HE SKATE BACKWARDS
OR FALL ON HIS FACE?

660
00:27:46,271 --> 00:27:47,638
We're nearly there.

661
00:27:47,705 --> 00:27:48,805
There's the roller rink.

662
00:27:48,871 --> 00:27:49,705
It's impressive.

663
00:27:49,771 --> 00:27:52,105
The things we get up to.

664
00:27:55,571 --> 00:27:57,205
That's a cool T-shirt.

665
00:27:57,971 --> 00:27:59,371
A SUCKER FOR GOODS

666
00:27:59,438 --> 00:28:01,805
It's got a serious retro vibe.

667
00:28:01,871 --> 00:28:03,605
A TIME CAPSULE OF THE ROLLER ERA

668
00:28:03,671 --> 00:28:04,905
It's so retro.

669
00:28:04,971 --> 00:28:07,171
I can't believe we're doing this.

670
00:28:07,238 --> 00:28:08,538
I love the vibe in here.

671
00:28:08,605 --> 00:28:11,871
FLASHING NEON LIGHTS

672
00:28:11,938 --> 00:28:13,038
A WIDE ROLLER RINK

673
00:28:13,105 --> 00:28:15,238
I feel like we've travelled back in time.

674
00:28:15,738 --> 00:28:16,805
This place has a great vibe.

675
00:28:16,871 --> 00:28:17,905
BUT…

676
00:28:17,971 --> 00:28:19,571
It's so dark.

677
00:28:19,638 --> 00:28:20,705
I can't see anything.

678
00:28:20,771 --> 00:28:22,105
- Really?
- Yes.

679
00:28:22,671 --> 00:28:23,871
Can they raise the brightness?

680
00:28:23,938 --> 00:28:25,971
SAFETY FIRST!
LET'S RAISE THE LIGHTS AND HAVE FUN

681
00:28:26,038 --> 00:28:28,071
I feel nervous.

682
00:28:28,138 --> 00:28:30,438
Oh, hello.
You're the University of Texas seniors.

683
00:28:31,738 --> 00:28:33,338
I'm the dance student.

684
00:28:33,405 --> 00:28:35,971
- I remember you.
- Aren't you a university professor?

685
00:28:36,038 --> 00:28:37,405
THEY LOOK MORE LIKE A PROFESSOR
IN THIS LIGHT

686
00:28:37,471 --> 00:28:38,871
It's dance season for us.

687
00:28:38,938 --> 00:28:40,705
Do they teach Korean dance
at the University of Texas?

688
00:28:40,771 --> 00:28:42,838
Of course, that's my major.

689
00:28:42,905 --> 00:28:43,838
GIGGLES

690
00:28:43,905 --> 00:28:45,238
Shouldn't Woo-jung wear it?

691
00:28:45,305 --> 00:28:47,205
- I…
- Look at you go.

692
00:28:47,271 --> 00:28:48,605
SMOOTH

693
00:28:48,671 --> 00:28:50,538
- It feels a bit different.
- Woo-jung.

694
00:28:50,605 --> 00:28:52,338
Don't forget you're not
in middle school anymore.

695
00:28:52,405 --> 00:28:53,571
You'll get hurt.

696
00:28:54,071 --> 00:28:57,638
THE PROFESSOR'S TURN

697
00:28:58,505 --> 00:29:00,538
- Oh, gosh.
- Be careful, Seo-jin.

698
00:29:00,605 --> 00:29:02,371
Be careful. Don't get hurt.

699
00:29:02,438 --> 00:29:03,905
You can't let your career end like this.

700
00:29:05,138 --> 00:29:07,071
It's even more slippery here.

701
00:29:07,138 --> 00:29:10,671
FIRST TIME IN 40 YEARS
STEPPING ONTO A ROLLER RINK

702
00:29:11,505 --> 00:29:13,038
ONE FOOT AFTER ANOTHER
REMEMBERING HIS YOUTH

703
00:29:13,105 --> 00:29:14,971
I think this was a bad idea.

704
00:29:17,638 --> 00:29:19,438
This is hard.

705
00:29:19,505 --> 00:29:22,038
You lose feeling in your legs as you ride.

706
00:29:22,105 --> 00:29:23,638
Show us going backwards.

707
00:29:23,705 --> 00:29:24,538
What?

708
00:29:25,271 --> 00:29:26,505
It's too hard.

709
00:29:26,571 --> 00:29:28,538
TIME HAS TAKEN
A HEAVIER TOLL THAN EXPECTED

710
00:29:29,871 --> 00:29:32,538
FORGET SKATING BACKWARDS
LET'S FOCUS ON GOING FORWARD

711
00:29:33,605 --> 00:29:35,405
Excuse me, Professor!

712
00:29:38,971 --> 00:29:40,205
You're doing pretty well.

713
00:29:40,271 --> 00:29:44,338
QUICKLY GETTING BACK INTO THE GROOVE

714
00:29:49,738 --> 00:29:51,338
What was that sound?

715
00:29:51,405 --> 00:29:53,738
- What was that? Are you okay?
- Who is that?

716
00:29:54,671 --> 00:29:56,338
- Who's fallen over?
- Darn it.

717
00:29:57,671 --> 00:29:59,038
THE DANCER AND PROFESSOR
DEFEATED BY THE POWER OF TIME

718
00:29:59,105 --> 00:30:00,505
What happened?

719
00:30:00,571 --> 00:30:02,238
Seo-jin!

720
00:30:02,738 --> 00:30:04,138
Grab onto me.

721
00:30:04,205 --> 00:30:05,638
YUNG-SUK WANTS TO HELP SEO-JIN

722
00:30:05,705 --> 00:30:07,038
BUT HIS FEET HAVE A MIND OF THEIR OWN

723
00:30:07,105 --> 00:30:08,305
Seo-jin…

724
00:30:08,371 --> 00:30:10,238
Oh, my gosh.

725
00:30:10,305 --> 00:30:11,605
CHAOS

726
00:30:11,671 --> 00:30:13,438
How did you both fall over?

727
00:30:13,505 --> 00:30:15,305
I fell over after watching him fall.

728
00:30:15,371 --> 00:30:17,271
HE'S UP AT LAST

729
00:30:17,338 --> 00:30:18,438
Seo-jin's leaving.

730
00:30:18,505 --> 00:30:19,571
CALLING IT A DAY AFTER 5 MINUTES

731
00:30:19,638 --> 00:30:20,671
He's leaving the rink.

732
00:30:24,271 --> 00:30:26,605
- Is your wrist okay?
- It's okay for now.

733
00:30:26,671 --> 00:30:29,371
- I fell…
- It's going to hurt tomorrow morning.

734
00:30:29,438 --> 00:30:31,905
- I landed slap bang on my bum.
- Me too.

735
00:30:33,638 --> 00:30:36,171
You need to move less as you get older.

736
00:30:36,805 --> 00:30:38,538
You can't roller skate at this age.

737
00:30:38,605 --> 00:30:39,671
It's so sad.

738
00:30:40,371 --> 00:30:42,371
Those skates look so sad.

739
00:30:42,438 --> 00:30:43,738
LIFELESS LIKE THEIR OWNER

740
00:30:43,805 --> 00:30:47,205
They've formed a train.
It's a party in there.

741
00:30:47,271 --> 00:30:48,671
- Let's go.
- Which foot first?

742
00:30:49,971 --> 00:30:51,405
The train to Chungcheong is taking off.

743
00:30:51,471 --> 00:30:53,805
- It's very fast-moving.
- Okay.

744
00:30:53,871 --> 00:30:55,338
YUNG-SUK'S FUN HACK
FORM A TRAIN

745
00:30:55,405 --> 00:30:56,838
Let's go!

746
00:30:57,505 --> 00:30:58,638
YUNG-SUK AND DAE-JU
ARE BOTH FROM CHUNGCHEONG

747
00:30:58,705 --> 00:30:59,938
SO, THEIR TRAIN IS NATURALLY SLOW

748
00:31:00,005 --> 00:31:01,705
One, two.

749
00:31:01,771 --> 00:31:04,338
- One, two.
- Yung-suk is doing all the work.

750
00:31:04,405 --> 00:31:06,471
- One, two.
- The train's growing.

751
00:31:06,538 --> 00:31:07,938
One, two.

752
00:31:08,005 --> 00:31:09,471
- Did we do it?
- All five are onboard.

753
00:31:09,538 --> 00:31:12,305
FIVE-CARRIAGE TRAIN SUCCESSFUL

754
00:31:12,371 --> 00:31:14,505
Today is Saturday night.

755
00:31:14,571 --> 00:31:16,371
NEXT ON THE AGENDA

756
00:31:16,438 --> 00:31:18,738
YUNG-SUK'S FUN HACK
ENTERTAINING DJ

757
00:31:19,638 --> 00:31:22,271
DJ YUNG-SUK DIALS UP THE FUN

758
00:31:22,338 --> 00:31:23,438
All right.

759
00:31:23,505 --> 00:31:27,571
Let's all cheer
for Lee Seo-jin and Lee Woo-jung.

760
00:31:27,638 --> 00:31:29,138
Raise your voices!

761
00:31:29,205 --> 00:31:30,538
CHEERING!

762
00:31:31,071 --> 00:31:32,605
THANKS GUYS…

763
00:31:32,671 --> 00:31:35,505
They can't get up
because they hurt their bums.

764
00:31:35,571 --> 00:31:38,705
- But they hope you all have a good time.
- He's having fun.

765
00:31:38,771 --> 00:31:41,038
ENJOY YOURSELVES

766
00:31:41,105 --> 00:31:42,605
SEO-JIN LEFT AFTER 5 MINUTES

767
00:31:42,671 --> 00:31:45,938
BUT IT'S BOOKED FOR 2 HOURS
SO THE CREW ARE STRUGGLING ON

768
00:31:46,005 --> 00:31:47,671
Isn't it L, O, V, E?

769
00:31:48,471 --> 00:31:50,305
OLD MAN DAE-JU STANDS ALONE
AMONG A CREW OF YOUNGSTERS

770
00:31:50,371 --> 00:31:51,438
This is right, isn't it?

771
00:31:53,171 --> 00:31:54,338
That was so cute.

772
00:31:55,105 --> 00:31:56,971
L, O, V, E.

773
00:31:57,871 --> 00:31:59,938
DAE-JU'S HAVING ALL THE FUN
JUST LIKE IN THE POOL

774
00:32:00,005 --> 00:32:01,571
Form a three-person train!

775
00:32:01,638 --> 00:32:02,938
- I knew it.
- Oh, no.

776
00:32:03,005 --> 00:32:04,238
I want in.

777
00:32:04,305 --> 00:32:06,071
Me too!

778
00:32:06,138 --> 00:32:08,405
Kim Dae-ju is out!

779
00:32:10,238 --> 00:32:13,005
HAPPINESS CUT SHORT

780
00:32:14,871 --> 00:32:15,705
Hello.

781
00:32:16,271 --> 00:32:18,471
I'm James from the neighboring village.

782
00:32:18,538 --> 00:32:19,471
YUNG-SUK'S FUN HACK
ROLE-PLAYING

783
00:32:19,538 --> 00:32:20,838
Well, you know.

784
00:32:20,905 --> 00:32:22,505
I've heard that in this neighborhood,

785
00:32:22,571 --> 00:32:26,038
the top dog is a guy called Jin.

786
00:32:26,105 --> 00:32:27,338
Let's go meet him.

787
00:32:33,638 --> 00:32:34,638
THE HOT GUY OF AUSTIN

788
00:32:34,705 --> 00:32:35,871
HEAD THROBBING

789
00:32:41,538 --> 00:32:43,438
THE TRAGIC FATE OF THE HOT GUY OF AUSTIN

790
00:32:43,505 --> 00:32:46,171
They're all in their thirties.

791
00:32:46,238 --> 00:32:48,071
If they fall,
they can get back up instantly.

792
00:32:48,138 --> 00:32:50,905
But we might need
an ambulance for these two.

793
00:32:50,971 --> 00:32:53,638
If one of them falls over,
they just laugh about it.

794
00:32:53,705 --> 00:32:56,871
If he falls over, everybody panics.

795
00:32:56,938 --> 00:32:58,538
INSTANT REACTION: CONDUCT A MEDICAL CHECK

796
00:32:58,605 --> 00:33:00,638
The reactions are so different.

797
00:33:00,705 --> 00:33:03,338
What's even sadder is
that Seo-jin and I are experienced.

798
00:33:03,405 --> 00:33:05,538
We thought we had this in the bag.

799
00:33:05,605 --> 00:33:07,071
You felt confident, right?

800
00:33:07,138 --> 00:33:07,971
But now we're both…

801
00:33:08,038 --> 00:33:08,905
RUBBING GENTLY

802
00:33:08,971 --> 00:33:11,071
Why do you keep rubbing it?
Is there something on your bum?

803
00:33:12,571 --> 00:33:14,305
I'm checking for a fracture.
I feel something moving.

804
00:33:14,371 --> 00:33:16,238
HE'S ACCIDENTALLY GAINED A MOVING TAILBONE

805
00:33:16,305 --> 00:33:18,671
You thought you'd be good at this, right?

806
00:33:18,738 --> 00:33:21,505
I thought I'd do okay.

807
00:33:21,571 --> 00:33:23,971
SEO-JIN TRUSTED HIS MIDDLE SCHOOL ABILITY

808
00:33:24,038 --> 00:33:25,471
- Same for me.
- But…

809
00:33:25,538 --> 00:33:29,105
I feel as if I've never skated before.

810
00:33:29,171 --> 00:33:31,371
It felt like my first time
putting on skates.

811
00:33:31,438 --> 00:33:32,905
I felt that way too.

812
00:33:32,971 --> 00:33:35,971
Seo-jin normally doesn't
do things like this for content.

813
00:33:36,038 --> 00:33:38,471
He always says, "No, thanks. You do it."

814
00:33:38,538 --> 00:33:41,638
But he was so eager
to get the skates and put them on.

815
00:33:41,705 --> 00:33:44,771
So, I figured he was feeling confident.

816
00:33:44,838 --> 00:33:47,971
I wanted to know how I'd do
since it's been 40 years.

817
00:33:48,038 --> 00:33:51,071
I wanted to know if I still had it.

818
00:33:51,738 --> 00:33:52,838
Grandpa.

819
00:33:52,905 --> 00:33:54,371
It's snack time, Grandpa.

820
00:33:56,105 --> 00:33:57,371
A CARE PACKAGE FOR A SICK PATIENT

821
00:33:57,438 --> 00:33:58,571
It's a snack drop-off visit.

822
00:33:58,638 --> 00:34:01,238
- It's a hospital visit.
- It's like feeding a bird on the street.

823
00:34:03,205 --> 00:34:05,405
The three of us should just leave.

824
00:34:05,471 --> 00:34:07,905
ONE MIND

825
00:34:07,971 --> 00:34:11,005
Let's get going.

826
00:34:11,071 --> 00:34:12,405
Let's do some day-drinking.

827
00:34:13,204 --> 00:34:16,005
They're having a blast in there.

828
00:34:16,071 --> 00:34:17,338
Let's leave quietly.

829
00:34:18,405 --> 00:34:20,638
Let's leave a message saying sorry.

830
00:34:20,704 --> 00:34:22,305
"I'm sorry, but we'd rather not see it."

831
00:34:22,371 --> 00:34:24,305
"I'm sorry, but I'm done skating."

832
00:34:24,371 --> 00:34:26,238
LAUGHING AWAY THEIR SORROW

833
00:34:27,138 --> 00:34:29,371
THE LAST MEAL IN TEXAS

834
00:34:34,871 --> 00:34:37,305
- What a great place.
- How did he find it?

835
00:34:37,371 --> 00:34:38,571
What's Seo-jin's secret?

836
00:34:38,638 --> 00:34:40,971
SEO-JIN'S RECOMMENDATION
AUSTIN'S BEST PORK BACKBONE STEW

837
00:34:41,038 --> 00:34:43,905
There's a glass for everybody.

838
00:34:43,971 --> 00:34:45,905
RAISING GLASSES TOGETHER

839
00:34:45,971 --> 00:34:48,005
- Cheers.
- Cheers.

840
00:34:48,071 --> 00:34:50,905
- It's been a great shoot.
- Great job.

841
00:34:50,971 --> 00:34:52,938
Cheers to the writers. You worked so hard.

842
00:34:53,005 --> 00:34:54,138
It's been a pleasure.

843
00:34:54,204 --> 00:34:56,538
Seo-jin, thanks for driving us around.

844
00:35:04,338 --> 00:35:06,038
In every restaurant,

845
00:35:06,105 --> 00:35:10,671
they always start by saying,
"I'll be your server today."

846
00:35:10,738 --> 00:35:12,938
That didn't happen much in New York.

847
00:35:13,005 --> 00:35:14,638
- It must be a Texas thing.
- I think so.

848
00:35:14,705 --> 00:35:16,705
New Yorkers aren't very friendly.

849
00:35:16,771 --> 00:35:18,971
That's a sudden change of tune.

850
00:35:19,038 --> 00:35:20,038
Don't you love New York?

851
00:35:20,105 --> 00:35:21,238
NEW YORK LOVER DISSES NEW YORK

852
00:35:21,305 --> 00:35:23,038
Did New York hurt you in some way?

853
00:35:23,105 --> 00:35:24,638
The people aren't very friendly.

854
00:35:25,338 --> 00:35:27,705
- He used to love New York.
- You filmed two seasons in New York.

855
00:35:27,771 --> 00:35:29,138
How could you change your mind?

856
00:35:29,205 --> 00:35:30,271
NEW YORK'S REPRESENTATIVE

857
00:35:30,338 --> 00:35:33,105
You can't turn back a changed heart.

858
00:35:33,171 --> 00:35:34,505
It's the same with men and women.

859
00:35:34,571 --> 00:35:37,371
When a relationship ends, that's it.

860
00:35:37,438 --> 00:35:39,205
You can't go back.

861
00:35:39,271 --> 00:35:41,538
Lee Seo-jin's giving us a lecture on love.

862
00:35:41,605 --> 00:35:42,738
This guy?

863
00:35:42,805 --> 00:35:46,338
He has no right to lecture us on love.

864
00:35:46,405 --> 00:35:48,338
To be honest, I don't know love.

865
00:35:49,571 --> 00:35:50,705
Oh, my bum hurts.

866
00:35:50,771 --> 00:35:52,505
HUMBLE WHEN IT COMES TO LOVE

867
00:35:52,571 --> 00:35:55,438
Lee Seo-jin shockingly confesses
he doesn't know love.

868
00:35:56,338 --> 00:36:00,738
The important thing is living happily.

869
00:36:00,805 --> 00:36:02,938
Isn't that right?
Live doing what you love.

870
00:36:03,005 --> 00:36:04,605
- That's right.
- What does love matter?

871
00:36:04,671 --> 00:36:07,505
Everyone lives differently.

872
00:36:07,571 --> 00:36:09,138
People make different choices in life.

873
00:36:09,205 --> 00:36:11,371
My love is Texas.

874
00:36:11,438 --> 00:36:13,971
SECOND SHOCKING CONFESSION
MY LOVE IS TEXAS

875
00:36:14,038 --> 00:36:15,238
SHY

876
00:36:15,305 --> 00:36:17,471
You're really something.
So, you're done with New York?

877
00:36:17,538 --> 00:36:18,838
New York is a past love?

878
00:36:18,905 --> 00:36:21,538
I don't think I ever loved New York.

879
00:36:21,605 --> 00:36:22,938
CONTINUING WITH SHOCKING CONFESSION
DENYING THE PAST

880
00:36:23,005 --> 00:36:24,438
That's how I feel now.

881
00:36:24,505 --> 00:36:26,338
It was my first love.

882
00:36:26,405 --> 00:36:28,105
But I've moved on. It was so long ago.

883
00:36:28,171 --> 00:36:29,371
What about Texas?

884
00:36:29,438 --> 00:36:31,005
That's an ongoing relationship.

885
00:36:31,705 --> 00:36:33,205
- It's your current love?
- It's still hot.

886
00:36:33,271 --> 00:36:34,771
- Your love for Texas is still hot.
- Yes.

887
00:36:34,838 --> 00:36:36,238
I think it will be my last love.

888
00:36:36,305 --> 00:36:38,238
I pray that's how it works out.

889
00:36:38,305 --> 00:36:39,538
It's my last love.

890
00:36:39,605 --> 00:36:42,071
Wouldn't you prefer to come
to a lovely place like this

891
00:36:42,138 --> 00:36:44,138
with someone you love
rather than for content?

892
00:36:44,205 --> 00:36:45,538
I'd have to care about their needs.

893
00:36:46,205 --> 00:36:47,605
Look at his face.

894
00:36:47,671 --> 00:36:49,905
HATES THE IDEA

895
00:36:49,971 --> 00:36:52,271
You don't seem to care about our needs.

896
00:36:52,338 --> 00:36:54,305
That's why I hang around with you.

897
00:36:54,371 --> 00:36:57,005
PEOPLE HE CAN COMFORTABLY IGNORE

898
00:36:57,071 --> 00:36:58,905
I'd have to put their needs above mine.

899
00:36:58,971 --> 00:37:00,605
- That's what it means to care.
- Right.

900
00:37:00,671 --> 00:37:02,238
Dating is putting
someone else's needs first.

901
00:37:02,305 --> 00:37:04,838
That gets harder to do over time.

902
00:37:04,905 --> 00:37:07,138
But from what I've seen,

903
00:37:07,205 --> 00:37:09,038
he does what he likes more than I do.

904
00:37:10,571 --> 00:37:12,605
That's why we can hang out together.

905
00:37:12,671 --> 00:37:15,105
We don't have to worry
about upsetting the other person.

906
00:37:15,171 --> 00:37:16,671
We're both honest about what we want.

907
00:37:16,738 --> 00:37:20,538
I prefer people being upfront
about what they want.

908
00:37:20,605 --> 00:37:22,705
I find it annoying when someone

909
00:37:22,771 --> 00:37:25,371
- just expects you to know.
- You can't read someone's mind.

910
00:37:25,438 --> 00:37:26,571
- I prefer his way.
- It's annoying--

911
00:37:26,638 --> 00:37:28,771
Tell me what you want, and I'll do it.

912
00:37:28,838 --> 00:37:31,105
Have I asked you for that much?

913
00:37:31,171 --> 00:37:32,471
All I asked for was a night in a motel

914
00:37:32,538 --> 00:37:34,038
- and a visit to the ranch.
- The criminal scenes.

915
00:37:34,105 --> 00:37:35,838
ANNOYED

916
00:37:35,905 --> 00:37:37,438
This is what I'm talking about.

917
00:37:37,505 --> 00:37:38,605
Some people say nothing

918
00:37:38,671 --> 00:37:40,438
and just expect me to know what they want.

919
00:37:40,505 --> 00:37:43,838
It's much easier
to hang out with people like you.

920
00:37:44,338 --> 00:37:45,605
You're all much better company.

921
00:37:45,671 --> 00:37:47,138
It doesn't feel like a compliment.

922
00:37:47,205 --> 00:37:49,905
I don't know if I should feel
pleased or insulted.

923
00:37:51,738 --> 00:37:54,671
- It's <i>gimbap.</i>
- It looks so fancy.

924
00:37:54,738 --> 00:37:56,205
GIMBAP

925
00:37:56,271 --> 00:37:57,638
TRUFFLE POTATO PANCAKE

926
00:37:57,705 --> 00:37:58,938
STIR-FRIED PORK

927
00:37:59,005 --> 00:38:00,338
SPICY RICE CAKES

928
00:38:00,405 --> 00:38:01,638
GRILLED SHORT RIBS

929
00:38:02,205 --> 00:38:04,471
AND THE PORK BACKBONE STEW
THEY'VE ALL BEEN WAITING FOR!

930
00:38:04,538 --> 00:38:06,438
The pork backbone stew is finally here.

931
00:38:06,505 --> 00:38:08,705
This is the perfect <i>mukbang</i> angle.

932
00:38:08,771 --> 00:38:10,138
All right. From now on,

933
00:38:10,205 --> 00:38:13,038
we're about to try
pork backbone stew in America.

934
00:38:13,105 --> 00:38:14,071
Short-Mouth Seo-jin.

935
00:38:14,138 --> 00:38:16,971
Short-Mouth Seo-jin,
why don't you take the first bite?

936
00:38:17,038 --> 00:38:18,238
- We need to boil it.
- What?

937
00:38:18,305 --> 00:38:20,505
- We need to heat it up.
- What do you mean?

938
00:38:20,571 --> 00:38:22,538
We need to take a bite first.

939
00:38:22,605 --> 00:38:23,871
Don't we need to stir it a bit?

940
00:38:23,938 --> 00:38:25,138
Before we do that,

941
00:38:25,205 --> 00:38:27,538
can you please say hello
to our subscribers first?

942
00:38:27,605 --> 00:38:28,871
Hello.

943
00:38:28,938 --> 00:38:30,538
This is Short-Mouth Seo-jin.

944
00:38:30,605 --> 00:38:32,038
Short-Mouth Seo-jin.

945
00:38:32,105 --> 00:38:34,571
This is a great angle.
It's perfect for a <i>mukbang.</i>

946
00:38:34,638 --> 00:38:37,338
Short-Mouth Seo-jin,
try it and tell us what you think.

947
00:38:37,405 --> 00:38:39,138
But I've been here before.
I brought you here.

948
00:38:39,205 --> 00:38:41,205
Our subscribers are waiting.

949
00:38:41,871 --> 00:38:44,171
They won't believe me.
So, you describe it.

950
00:38:44,238 --> 00:38:47,238
I brought you here
because I think it tastes great.

951
00:38:47,305 --> 00:38:49,871
BIG-MOUTH YUNG-SUK TAKES A BITE

952
00:38:51,838 --> 00:38:53,171
It's not sweet.

953
00:38:53,238 --> 00:38:55,938
It usually needs sugar to taste good.

954
00:38:56,005 --> 00:38:57,038
But this is different.

955
00:38:57,105 --> 00:38:59,071
I know my food.

956
00:39:00,071 --> 00:39:01,738
Are you paid to promote this?

957
00:39:01,805 --> 00:39:03,738
LEE SEO-JIN IS NOT PAID TO PROMOTE
TEXAS OR BACKBONE STEW

958
00:39:03,805 --> 00:39:07,338
I think Fort Worth was the most fun.

959
00:39:07,405 --> 00:39:08,771
LOOKING BACK ON THE TEXAS TRIP

960
00:39:08,838 --> 00:39:10,305
- Where? Fort Worth?
- Yes, Fort Worth.

961
00:39:10,371 --> 00:39:13,138
I loved it all,
from the bags to the outfits.

962
00:39:13,205 --> 00:39:15,171
I really recommend that.

963
00:39:15,238 --> 00:39:18,071
- He doesn't even help you choose.
- Which merch store did you like best?

964
00:39:18,138 --> 00:39:21,438
We shopped in Dallas and Texas,
and we went to the NASA store.

965
00:39:21,505 --> 00:39:23,205
My favorite was the University of Texas.

966
00:39:23,271 --> 00:39:24,971
- Of course.
- Their color is so pretty.

967
00:39:25,038 --> 00:39:27,171
The University of Texas is the best.

968
00:39:27,238 --> 00:39:30,505
Most of my clothes are from there.

969
00:39:31,271 --> 00:39:32,671
In my opinion, it's the best.

970
00:39:32,738 --> 00:39:35,505
I've got all sorts of their merchandise,
including a golf T-shirt.

971
00:39:35,571 --> 00:39:36,771
On top of that,

972
00:39:37,505 --> 00:39:40,538
you can buy things like NFL merchandise

973
00:39:40,605 --> 00:39:42,271
even in Korea.

974
00:39:42,338 --> 00:39:44,071
But you can't buy
University of Texas goods in Korea.

975
00:39:44,138 --> 00:39:45,371
Of course not.

976
00:39:45,438 --> 00:39:48,905
That's like buying
Kyungpook University goods in the US.

977
00:39:48,971 --> 00:39:50,538
- I mean…
- Maybe if it was Seoul University…

978
00:39:50,605 --> 00:39:52,038
But a regional university is so random.

979
00:39:52,105 --> 00:39:53,305
They don't ship overseas.

980
00:39:53,371 --> 00:39:54,638
A Dodgers fan won't care

981
00:39:54,705 --> 00:39:57,205
if you pass by
wearing Dodgers merchandise.

982
00:39:57,271 --> 00:39:59,005
For instance, Itaewon.

983
00:39:59,071 --> 00:40:01,371
American people will get excited

984
00:40:01,438 --> 00:40:03,338
if they see you wearing
the University of Texas logo.

985
00:40:03,405 --> 00:40:04,571
Imagine coming to the US

986
00:40:04,638 --> 00:40:07,005
and seeing the Kyungpook University logo.

987
00:40:07,071 --> 00:40:08,338
IT'S EASY TO UNDERSTAND
WHY THAT WOULD BE EXCITING

988
00:40:08,405 --> 00:40:09,305
You would feel so connected

989
00:40:09,371 --> 00:40:11,538
to an American wearing
the Chungnam University logo.

990
00:40:11,605 --> 00:40:13,171
Go to Itaewon or Dongducheon.

991
00:40:13,238 --> 00:40:15,671
So many Americans
will greet you with this sign.

992
00:40:15,738 --> 00:40:18,138
- Are there many Texas alumni?
- Even if they're not alumni,

993
00:40:18,205 --> 00:40:20,671
any Texas resident
will go crazy for the logo.

994
00:40:20,738 --> 00:40:22,571
LEE SEO-JIN, NEW YORK UNIVERSITY ALUMNUS

995
00:40:22,638 --> 00:40:25,838
As for New York…

996
00:40:25,905 --> 00:40:27,771
Let's say you go to New York.

997
00:40:27,838 --> 00:40:30,838
If you travel down from Boston,

998
00:40:30,905 --> 00:40:32,838
you must visit Harvard University.

999
00:40:32,905 --> 00:40:34,438
Do they have their own merchandise?

1000
00:40:34,505 --> 00:40:35,938
- Of course.
- You can buy their goods

1001
00:40:36,005 --> 00:40:39,471
anywhere in Boston,
not just at Harvard University.

1002
00:40:39,538 --> 00:40:42,105
Then, you need to drop by MIT.

1003
00:40:42,171 --> 00:40:44,971
It's the only thing
I recommend you spend money on.

1004
00:40:45,038 --> 00:40:48,371
If you go further south,
you get to Yale in Connecticut.

1005
00:40:48,438 --> 00:40:50,371
Yale merchandise is also very pretty.

1006
00:40:50,438 --> 00:40:51,971
